1. Write the loop integral:  
$$i\Gamma^{(1)}
=(-ie)(ie)(-i)(i)\,gP_L\int\frac{d^Dq}{(2\pi)^D}
\frac{\gamma^\mu(\slashed p_1-\slashed q + m_e)(2p_3+q)_\mu}
{[(p_1-q)^2-m_e^2][(p_3+q)^2-m_\phi^2]\,q^2}\,. $$

2. In the UV limit ($q\to\infty$), set external momenta $p_i$ and masses $m_i$ to zero. The denominators become approximately $(q^2)^3$. The numerator becomes:
$$N \approx \gamma^\mu(-\slashed q)q_\mu=-q^2$$
The divergent part of the integral can thus be approximated:
$$i\Gamma^{(1)}_{\rm div}
\approx i\,g\,e^2P_L\int\frac{d^Dq}{(2\pi)^D}\frac{-1}{q^4} = -i\,g\,e^2P_L\int\frac{d^Dq}{(2\pi)^D}\frac{1}{q^4}$$

3. Use dimensional regularization. The Minkowski-space integral gives a pole term:  
$$\int\frac{d^Dq}{(2\pi)^D}\frac1{q^4}
=\frac{i}{16\pi^2}\,\frac{2}{\epsilon}\,+\text{finite}.$$  

4. Therefore:  
$$i\Gamma^{(1)}_{\rm div}
= (-i\,g\,e^2P_L) \left( \frac{i}{16\pi^2}\,\frac{2}{\epsilon} \right) = \frac{g e^2}{8\pi^2} \frac{1}{\epsilon} P_L
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
C=\frac{e^2}{8\pi^2}\,. $$
